  "prompt": "What are the chances of the electoral college changing vote for Clinton?",
  "response": "As of my last update in October 2023, the likelihood of the Electoral College changing its vote for a candidate after the election has occurred is exceedingly low. The Electoral College is composed of electors pledged to vote for their party's candidate based on the outcome of the popular vote in their respective states. While there have been instances of \"faithless electors\" who did not vote for the candidate to whom they were pledged, these occurrences are rare and typically do not affect the overall outcome of an election.\n\nTo change their vote, electors would have to go against the will of the voters in their state, which could lead to significant political and legal repercussions. Additionally, some states have laws binding electors to their pledged candidate, further reducing the chances of a successful pivot.\n\nThe practical effect is that once the electoral votes have been cast and certified, the chance of them changing significantly or favoring a different candidate, such as Hillary Clinton in an election context after she lost, is very slim.",
